The volume dial is the component of a notebook that controls the volume of the notebook's speakers. The volume dial can be controlled by dedicated control buttons on the EasyControl Bar (Volume+/Volume-), by hot key function, or via a digital display, and its range of volume is from 11 to 8.
The unit of measure for the Volume dial column.
The material used in the casework of the notebook. Examples include polycarbonate ABS, magnesium + polycarbonate ABS, or 1.
The unit of measure for the Casework material column.

Security features of a notebook. This includes any security solutions that are built into the notebook, as well as any security measures that a user can add on to the notebook themselves. This can include, but is not limited to, hard disk drive passwords, power-on passwords, security lock slots, supervisor passwords, and fingerprint readers.
The unit of measure for the Security features column.

The manufacturer of the motherboard for the given notebook product. Motherboards are the main printed circuit board (PCB) in a notebook, and they hold the central processing unit (CPU), memory, and connectors for other devices in the notebook.
The unit of measure for the Motherboard manufacturer column.

The Wireless communication data transfer rate is the speed at which data is transferred between the notebook and other devices via wireless communication. The transfer rate is measured in Mbit/s. The minimum value is 1.0 Mbit/s, and the maximum value is 1000.0 Mbit/s.
The unit of measure for the Wireless communication data transfer rate column.
This column contains the various special features of the notebook, such as ENERGY STAR qualification, enhanced Intel SpeedStep Technology, SM BIOS compliance, and HD Audio support.
The unit of measure for the Special features column.
The expansion type of the notebook, e.g. '2 x memory slots', '1 x ExpressCard slot', etc.
The unit of measure for the Expansion type column.

A 2D graphics accelerator is a type of graphics accelerator that primarily accelerates 2D graphics, usually using hardware-accelerated BitBLT operations to accelerate simple 2D operations, and is included with most modern GPUs.
The unit of measure for the 2D graphics accelerator column.
Storage drive type for a given row. "notebook"
The unit of measure for the Storage drive desktop or notebook? column.
Indicates the presence of a keyboard key for the euro currency.
The unit of measure for the Keyboard euro key column.
The weight of the notebook's package in grams. Packages of notebooks weigh between 1.0 g and 17000.0 g.
The unit of measure for the Package weight column.

A vector processing unit, or VPU, is an extension of a central processing unit, or CPU. It is a component that enhances the capability of the CPU to perform arithmetical and logical operations on arrays of data that may be simple or complex. This column indicates if the processor has this technology.
The unit of measure for the Intel Advanced Vector Extensions column.
A notebook's Intel Smart Sound Technology availability. False indicates that the notebook does not have this feature, and true indicates that it does.
The unit of measure for the Intel Smart Sound Technology column.
Physical type of the stylus pen for the laptop. Values are either Active or Passive.
The unit of measure for the Stylus pen type column.
The processor series that the notebook is compatible with. This may refer to the same processor across multiple generations and should not be used to refer to specific processors.
The unit of measure for the Compatible processor series column.

The Micro-USB 3.2 Gen 1 (3.1 Gen 1) ports quantity refers to the number of ports on the notebook that are compatible with the Micro-USB 3.2 Gen 1 and 3.1 Gen 1 standards. This standard provides a nominal data rate of 480 Mbit/s.
The unit of measure for the Micro-USB 3.2 Gen 1 (3.1 Gen 1) ports quantity column.

Indicates whether the notebook has a port replicator. Port replicators allow the connection of multiple peripherals to a notebook, such as monitors, hard drives, and other devices. This field is set to true if the notebook has a port replicator, and false if it does not.
The unit of measure for the Port replicator column.

The Scalability column indicates the scalability of the notebook. The options are 1S or 2S, with 1S being the least scalable and 2S being the most scalable. The 1S option is usually sufficient for basic tasks such as web browsing, word processing, and watching videos. The 2S option is recommended for more demanding tasks such as gaming, video editing, and running multiple applications simultaneously.
The unit of measure for the Scalability column.
The thermal solution specification of the notebook. This includes the type of thermal solution, such as PCG 2015C, PCG 2011C, etc.
The unit of measure for the Thermal solution specification column.

The keyboard easy keys are the additional keys on a notebook keyboard that make it easier to use. This includes the keys that are used to turn on/off the notebook, as well as keys that are used to change the volume or brightness of the screen. The keyboard easy keys are typically found on the top of the keyboard, and are labeled with the function they perform.
The unit of measure for the Keyboard easy keys column.

The BIOS ACPI column contains information about the Advanced Configuration and Power Interface (ACPI) that is used by the BIOS of the notebook. The ACPI is responsible for controlling the power state of the hardware components of the notebook, as well as handling the hardware configuration of the notebook. The format of the ACPI is a string that contains the version number of the ACPI specification that is supported by the notebook.
The unit of measure for the BIOS ACPI column.
The location of the second display on the notebook. The location can be either on the top or on the bottom of the notebook.
The unit of measure for the Second display location column.

The docking station graphics adapter model refers to the model of the graphics adapter that is used in the docking station of the notebook. The graphics adapter is the component that produces the output images that are displayed on the notebook's screen. Examples of graphics adapter models include 'NVIDIA GeForce GTX 970', 'NVIDIA GeForce GTX 980', and 'AMD Radeon HD R9 290'.
The unit of measure for the Docking station graphics adapter model column.

The amount of memory in the graphics adapter of the docking station. Docking stations provide a way to connect peripherals such as monitors, keyboards, mice, printers, and external hard drives to a laptop computer or other portable device. Docking stations typically provide additional ports and connectors beyond what is built into the portable device and may also provide additional power to run or charge the device.
The unit of measure for the Docking station graphics adapter memory column.

Column Name Raw: Docking station graphics adapter memory type.18842
Column Name: Docking station graphics adapter memory type
Column Definition: The docking station graphics adapter memory type refers to the type of memory used in the graphics adapter of the docking station for the given notebook product. The graphics adapter memory type can be one of many types, such as GDDR5.

Column Name Raw: Docking station graphics adapter memory type.18842.unit
Column Name: Docking station graphics adapter memory type_unit
Column Definition: The unit of measure for the Docking station graphics adapter memory type column.
The docking station power supply column contains the measurement of the power supply for the docking station in Watts.  The minimum value is 1.0 W and the maximum value is 450.0 W.
The unit of measure for the Docking station power supply column.

The docking station LAN controller is the network card that allows a notebook to connect to a docking station. This provides additional connectivity options and ports to the notebook. Examples of network cards that can be used in this manner are the Killer Gb LAN and the Killer E2500 Gigabit Ethernet Controller.
The unit of measure for the Docking station LAN controller column.
The size of the hard disk drive (HDD) that is supported by the docking station of the notebook. The value should be in inches and the format should be "3.5" or "2.5".
The unit of measure for the Docking station supported HDD size column.

Whether or not the notebook has built-in docking station speakers. If the notebook has built-in docking station speakers, the value will be True. If the notebook does not have built-in docking station speakers, the value will be False.
The unit of measure for the Docking station built-in speakers column.
The number of audio output channels supported by the docking station of the notebook. This includes both built-in and external audio output channels.
The unit of measure for the Docking station audio output channels column.
The power output of the docking station speakers in watts (W).
The unit of measure for the Docking station speakers RMS power column.
The amount of power that the subwoofer of the given docking station for a notebook has, in watts (W).
The unit of measure for the Docking station subwoofer RMS power column.
Whether the notebook has a docking station with a mini DisplayPort
The unit of measure for the Docking station mini DisplayPort column.
Physical connection for a laptop to be placed in a docking station for charging and to connect to peripherals such as monitors, keyboards, and mice.
The unit of measure for the Docking station power connector column.

A Labelflash indicates whether the laptop has a customized label or not. False indicates that the laptop's label is not customized by the manufacturer, while true indicates that the laptop's label is customized by the manufacturer.
The unit of measure for the Labelflash column.
Features of the laptop that provide comfort and efficiency when using it, such as whether it has touch-sensitive controls or an adjustable notebook stand.
The unit of measure for the Ergonomics column.
Range of humidity a laptop can operate, in percent and formatted as 'X - Y%' e.g. '10 - 90%' or '20 - 80%'
The unit of measure for the Relative humidity column.
Processor technology refers to the type of processor used in the notebook. Examples include Intel Centrino 2, Hyper-Threading, Intel Centrino 2 w/ vPro, and Intel SpeedStep.
The unit of measure for the Processor technology column.
A string that is the UNSPSC code identifying the product. The UNSPSC is a standard maintained by GS1 which provides a consistent way to identify items across a supply chain.
The unit of measure for the UNSPSC-code column.
Dimensions of the package for the notebook. Provides three measurements (width, depth, and height). All measurements are in millimeters.
The unit of measure for the Package dimensions (WxDxH) column.

The motherboard southbridge describes the type of motherboard chipset and is typically named after the manufacturer followed by a number. It is also known as the chipset, southbridge, or I/O controller.
The unit of measure for the Motherboard southbridge column.
True key status of the product. "True" indicates the product has a true key, and "False" indicates the product does not have a true key.
The unit of measure for the True Key column.
The model of the coprocessor in the laptop.
The unit of measure for the Coprocessor model column.
The type of audio adapter, which can be an integrated sound card or a separate expansion card, that is used to provide input and output audio functionality for the notebook.
The unit of measure for the Audio adapter type column.

The resolution of the main camera on the notebook. The resolution is a measure of how many megapixels the camera can capture. The format of the resolution is a non-negative integer, and the minimum resolution is 0.3 megapixels, while the maximum resolution is 8.0 megapixels.
The unit of measure for the Main camera resolution (numeric) column.

Intel Memory Protection Extensions (Intel MPX) is a set of hardware-based memory protection extensions to the x86 architecture. It is designed to prevent memory corruption and to protect against buffer overruns and underruns. The extensions provide finer-grained control over memory access permissions, allowing the operating system to restrict access to certain memory regions to only privileged software. This can prevent malicious or buggy software from accessing or modifying data in a way that could cause a system crash or other unintended behavior.
The unit of measure for the Intel Memory Protection Extensions (Intel MPX) column.
A notebook's Intel Instruction Replay Technology determines whether the Intel processor supports the ability to record and replay instructions that were executed by the processor.
The unit of measure for the Intel Instruction Replay Technology column.

The amount of memory on the notebook that is used to store data that is being used or that will be used in the future by the notebook. The cache memory is important for the notebook to be able to quickly access data without having to retrieve it from the main memory, which is much slower. The cache memory is measured in MB (megabytes).
The unit of measure for the Cache memory column.
The maximum internal memory of the notebook, measured in GB. Ranges from 4.0 to 32.0 GB, both inclusive.
The unit of measure for the Maximum internal memory column.
The number of Thunderbolt 2 ports on the notebook. It is an integer value represented by a string and can vary from 1.0 to 9.0
The unit of measure for the Thunderbolt 2 ports quantity column.

The maximum graphics adapter memory of the notebook. This is the amount of memory dedicated to the graphics adapter of the notebook. The graphics adapter is responsible for rendering the graphics on the notebook's display. The format of this column is a floating-point number in megabytes (MB).
The unit of measure for the Maximum graphics adapter memory column.
Indicates whether the notebook has a self-encrypting drive. Options include True or False (or equivalent).
The unit of measure for the Self-Encrypting Drive (SED) column.

A string that describes the speakers of the notebook. This may include whether the speakers are built-in or detachable and the number and type of speakers. Examples include "Dynaudio", "stereo", and "2 built-in stereo speakers".
The unit of measure for the Speakers column.

A boolean value that describes whether the notebook uses AMD FreeSync technology or not. This is a proprietary synchronization technology developed by AMD, it allows the display to adapt its refresh rate to the frame rate of the content, which in turn offers a very fluid gaming experience and a very smooth visual experience.
The unit of measure for the AMD FreeSync column.
Whether the notebook has a noise-canceling microphone or speaker, which is a microphone or speaker that cancels out background noise to make the audio clearer.
The unit of measure for the Noise-canceling column.
Whether the device has a ROG XG Mobile port or not
The unit of measure for the ROG XG Mobile port column.
Whether the notebook has a docking station with a dual link DVI.
The unit of measure for the Docking station Dual Link DVI column.
A string used to identify a product's classification, used to identify and track products in a supply chain.", 'min_length': 10
The unit of measure for the Commodity Classification Automated Tracking System (CCATS) column.
Temperature range that the laptop operates in, in Celsius. The range is listed as two values separated by a hyphen, for example: '0 - 35'. Both values are integers.
The unit of measure for the Operating temperature (T-T) column.
Information about the multimedia capabilities of the notebook. This can include the type of audio support, speakers, headphone/line out ports, microphone, webcam, and other related features.
The unit of measure for the Multimedia column.
Wireless standard of the notebook, e.g. 'Bluetooth 3.0; ThinkPad 11b/g/n Wi-Fi wireless', 'Bluetooth 4.0; Lenovo BGN Wireless', '11'.
The unit of measure for the Wireless standard column.
A string representing the notebook's antenna. It has a minimum length of 100 characters and can contain spaces.
The unit of measure for the Antenna column.
Memory description of the notebook. This includes the RAM of both the hard drive and any external RAM which can be used with the device as well.
The unit of measure for the Memory description column.
Functions pertaining to the energy saving capabilities of the laptop, such as hibernation mode and power management.
The unit of measure for the Energy saving functions column.

Indicate whether the laptop has the given multimedia feature or not. Return a string with values 'Yes' or 'No'. If the laptop has the feature, return 'Yes'. If the laptop does not have the feature, return 'No'.  For the example provided return 'Yes'.
The unit of measure for the Multimedia features column.
The Worldwide AC compatibility column contains information about whether the notebook is compatible with AC power worldwide. The column is a string that can be either 'Y' or 'N'.
The unit of measure for the Worldwide AC compatibility column.

Features that are related to the wireless connectivity of the notebook. This can include information such as the type of wireless, the standard that it supports, and any additional information about the wireless card or chipset.
The unit of measure for the Wireless features column.
Weight of the notebook in pounds, ranging from a minimum of 1.0 to a maximum of 7.19
The unit of measure for the Weight (imperial) column.

Load-bearing capacity of the intermodal container (20ft) in the form of a note. The format of the note is a string that includes corner posts and the number of posts and planks that make up the loading surface.
The unit of measure for the Intermodal container (20ft) loading note column.
A string that indicates whether the device has the HP Touchpoint Manager software installed. The value is either True or False.
The unit of measure for the HP Touchpoint Manager column.

Column Name Raw: Master (outer) cases per intermodal container (40ft, HC).31924
Column Name: Master (outer) cases per intermodal container (40ft, HC)
Column Definition: The number of notebook computers that can fit in a 40ft high cube intermodal container. The minimum value is 1 and the maximum value is 5016.

Column Name Raw: Master (outer) cases per intermodal container (40ft, HC).31924.unit
Column Name: Master (outer) cases per intermodal container (40ft, HC)_unit
Column Definition: The unit of measure for the Master (outer) cases per intermodal container (40ft, HC) column.
The outer cases of the product. This is the number of cases that are shipped with the product. The value is measured in pieces (pc).
The unit of measure for the Master (outer) cases per intermodal container (20ft) column.
Indicates whether the notebook includes a headset with purchase or not. "True" indicates that a headset is included, and "False" indicates no headset is included with purchase.
The unit of measure for the Headset included column.
The type of storage drive present in the notebook. Can be SATA, SSD or any other type of storage drive.
The unit of measure for the Storage drive type column.
The DVD read speed of the notebook, representing the rate at which the DVD drive in the notebook can read data from a DVD, with a minimum of 1.0 x.
The unit of measure for the DVD read speed column.
The version of the Thunderbolt port installed on the laptop, in the form of an integer
The unit of measure for the Thunderbolt version column.
The speed at which the notebook's DVD-ROM drive can read a disc, with a minimum of 1.0x and a maximum of 8.0x.
The unit of measure for the DVD-ROM read speed column.
Second adapter in a laptop that can be swapped out with another one without having to shut down the computer
The unit of measure for the Hot-swap second graphics adapter column.
Cache internal refers to the internal cache size of the notebook. It ranges from **1.0** MB to **1.0** MB
The unit of measure for the Cache internal column.
The speed at which the notebook's DVD drive can write to a DVD, in multiples of 1x. 1x is equivalent to a constant bitrate of 11.08 MB/s.
The unit of measure for the DVD write speed column.
The speed at which the DVD drive can rewrite a DVD. The values are in multiples of x, with 1.0 x being the slowest and 8.0 x being the fastest.
The unit of measure for the DVD rewrite speed column.
True if the notebook has a convertible hinge; false otherwise.
The unit of measure for the Convertible hinge test column.
Amount of Polyethylene terephthalate in grams in each package.
The unit of measure for the Polyethylene terephthalate (PET) content per package column.
A boolean value that describes if the device has the HP Sure Connect 2.0 functionality or not. This can also be known as Wifi
The unit of measure for the HP Sure Connect 2.0 column.
The current of the USB port when charging
The unit of measure for the USB charging current column.
The writing speed for the DVD+R drive in the notebook, ranging from 1.0 x to 8.0 x.
The unit of measure for the DVD+R speed column.

The DVD+RW speed of the notebook. The speed is the maximum speed at which the DVD+RW drive can write to a DVD+RW disc. The format of the value is a floating-point number followed by 'x', for example, '4.0', '6.0', '2.4', '1.0' x.
The unit of measure for the DVD+RW speed column.

The DVD-R speed of the notebook. The speed is given in x, where x is the maximum write speed of the DVD-R drive in Mbps. For example, 8.0 x means that the DVD-R drive has a maximum write speed of 8 Mbps.
The unit of measure for the DVD-R speed column.
The DVD-RW speed of the notebook. The speed is the maximum speed at which the DVD-RW drive can write to a DVD-RW disc. The format of the value is a floating-point number.
The unit of measure for the DVD-RW speed column.

Whether the notebook product has a 4K streaming feature. A value of True indicates that the product has a 4K streaming feature, while a value of False indicates that the product does not have a 4K streaming feature.
The unit of measure for the 4K streaming column.
The number of cores in the on-board graphics adapter for the given notebook product.
The unit of measure for the On-board graphics adapter cores column.
Boolean value indicating whether the notebook comes with HP Drive Encryption or not. true if the notebook includes HP Drive Encryption, false otherwise.
The unit of measure for the HP Drive Encryption column.
Whether the hard drive can be swapped on the go
The unit of measure for the Hot-swap column.
Values for this column are a list of countries, where the notebook is available for purchase or shipping.
The unit of measure for the Model availability column.
A string indicating which keyboards are supported by the palmrest. This can be one or more of Belgian, German, or Italian.
The unit of measure for the Palmrest keyboards supported column.
The browsing time of the laptop over Wi-Fi. This is specified in hours and can range from 10.0 to 15.0 hours.
The unit of measure for the Browsing time (Wi-Fi) column.

Physical pen device that is compatible with the notebook and is used for accurately drawing, writing, or pointing on the screen. These pens are usually stored by friction in an internal garage in the notebook itself or clipped to one of the ports.
The unit of measure for the HP stylus pen type column.
The graphics adapter interface of the notebook. This can be "Integrated" or a specific PCIe version/interface, e.g. PCIe x4, PCIe x16, PCIe Express 2.0.
The unit of measure for the Graphics adapter interface column.
A string that contains the software that is downloadable with the laptop. Can be operating systems, or other productivity software like Microsoft Office.
The unit of measure for the Downloadable software column.
The maximum speed at which the laptop\'s DVD drive can write to a double layer DVD, with "x" being a placeholder for a variable measurement.
The unit of measure for the Double Layer DVD write speed column.

The speed at which the notebook's Double Layer DVD drive can read. It is measured in multiples of x, with 1.0 x being the slowest and 8.0 x being the fastest. Note that this is the speed for reading DVDs, not the overall speed of the computer.
The unit of measure for the Double Layer DVD read speed column.
Memory upgrade of the notebook. Example values: '8.0', '4.0', '2.0', '16.0', '32.0' GB. Note that the minimum value is 1.0 GB, but there aren't any examples of this in the provided data.
The unit of measure for the Memory upgrade column.
True if the device has a memory card slot and false if it does not.
The unit of measure for the Memory card slot(s) column.
A list of Bluetooth profiles that the notebook computer supports, such as A2DP, WAPB, DID, HCRP, and PBAP.
The unit of measure for the Bluetooth profiles column.
The maximum external resolution that the notebook product can support for video output, specified as width x height pixels.
The unit of measure for the External video modes resolution (max) column.

The networking speed of the notebook, which is the rate at which data is transferred between the notebook and other devices. This column will contain a string that represents the networking speed, such as '10/100/1000 Mbps Base-TX', '10/100 Mbps Base-TX', '10BASE-T/100BASE-TX', '10/100 Mbps', or '10BASE-T/100BASE-TX/1000BASE-T'.
The unit of measure for the Networking speed column.
Video adapter, bus information. Describes the video adapter and bus of the notebook. Can be one of PCI Express, AGP, or integrated graphics.
The unit of measure for the Video adapter, bus column.

Whether the notebook can be connected to an external display simultaneously with its built-in screen. If the notebook has a built-in screen and the ability to connect to an external display at the same time, this value is 'True'. If the notebook has either no built-in screen, or no ability to connect to an external display, this value is 'False'.
The unit of measure for the Simultaneous external display column.

The data transfer rate is the speed at which data is transferred between the notebook's storage and another device. This column contains the data transfer rate in Gbit/s, which is a measure of how fast data can be transferred. The minimum value is 1.0 Gbit/s, which means that data can be transferred at a rate of 1.0 Gbit/s or faster. The maximum value is also 1.0 Gbit/s, which means that the data transfer rate is not greater than 1.0 Gbit/s.
The unit of measure for the Data transfer rate column.
The type of bays that the notebook has.  For example, 'Ultrabay Enhanced', 'Media Bay', 'Serial Ultrabay Slim', 'Ultrabay Slim'.
The unit of measure for the Type of bays column.
The number of RJ-45 ports on the notebook. RJ-45 ports are a type of network port that is commonly found on notebooks.
The unit of measure for the RJ-45 ports quantity column.
A boolean value that indicates whether the notebook has an HDMI port or not. This column must have one of the following values: 'True' or 'False'.
The unit of measure for the HDMI column.
The number of WLAN antennas for the notebook.
The unit of measure for the Number of WLAN antennas column.
The number of buttons on the pointing stick of the notebook.
The unit of measure for the Number of pointing stick buttons column.

The capacity of the secondary hard disk drive (HDD) in the notebook, measured in gigabytes (GB). This value must be a positive integer, representing the exact capacity of the HDD. For example, 750.0 GB.
The unit of measure for the HDD 2 capacity column.
The CD-ROM read speed of the notebook, measured in x (ex. 24.0 x, 1.0 x).
The unit of measure for the CD-ROM read speed column.

Aluminium is often used in the design of high-end notebooks. It is a good conductor of electricity, and also aids in the dissipation of heat from the notebook. This column indicates whether the notebook's design makes use of machined aluminium or not.
The unit of measure for the Machined aluminium design column.

Column Name Raw: Number of Graphics & IMC Die Transistors.10325
Column Name: Number of Graphics & IMC Die Transistors
Column Definition: The number of Graphics & IMC die transistors in the notebook.

Column Name Raw: Number of Graphics & IMC Die Transistors.10325.unit
Column Name: Number of Graphics & IMC Die Transistors_unit
Column Definition: The unit of measure for the Number of Graphics & IMC Die Transistors column.
The number of QPI links for the laptop. It is an integer value, with a minimum of 1.0 and a maximum of 15.0
The unit of measure for the Number of QPI links column.
Battery capacity of the tablet version of the product, in mAh. Ranges from 1.0 to 42800.0 mAh.
The unit of measure for the Battery capacity (tablet) column.
The HD DVD-ROM read speed of the notebook, in x speed. Min: 1.0 x, Max: 8.0 x
The unit of measure for the HD DVD-ROM read speed column.
The HD DVD-ROM write speed of the notebook, in x.
The unit of measure for the HD DVD-ROM write speed column.
The charging time of the notebook. This is the time it takes to charge the battery of the notebook to its full capacity. The unit of measurement is minutes. Format is decimal.
The unit of measure for the Charging time column.
Boolean value indicating presence of Hall sensor in notebook.
The unit of measure for the Hall sensor column.
The display size of the notebook. The size is provided in a format of HxV, where H is the height and V is the width of the display.
The unit of measure for the Display size (HxV) (imperial) column.
The type of controller used for the storage drive. Examples include SATA, SATA II, Serial ATA-150, SATA Hard Disk Drive, and SMART PATA.
The unit of measure for the Storage drive controller column.

The ATI XGP ports quantity refers to the number of ATI XGP ports that are on the notebook. The ATI XGP is a high-performance graphics card that is used for gaming and other graphics-intensive tasks. The quantity of the ports is important because it determines how many monitors or other devices can be connected to the notebook.
The unit of measure for the ATI XGP ports quantity column.
The power plug types that are included with the notebook. This can be a list of power plug types or a single power plug type.
The unit of measure for the Included power plug types column.

Column Name Raw: Mouse included on selected markets only.36393
Column Name: Mouse included on selected markets only
Column Definition: Mouse included on selected markets only. This column indicates whether or not a mouse is included with the notebook in the selected market. The value is either True or False.

Column Name Raw: Mouse included on selected markets only.36393.unit
Column Name: Mouse included on selected markets only_unit
Column Definition: The unit of measure for the Mouse included on selected markets only column.
Whether or not the product was produced sustainably. This is a pass/fail test, so the value will be either true or false.
The unit of measure for the Sustainability compliance column.

The Compatible products column contains information about which products are compatible with the notebook. This information is usually found in the product manual or on the manufacturer's website.

The column may contain a list of compatible products, or it may contain a single compatible product. If the column contains a list of compatible products, the list should be separated by commas. If the column contains a single compatible product, the product should be listed as a string.

For example, the Compatible products column may contain the following values:
Windows 7 Professional 64-bit, Windows 8 Pro 64-bit, Windows 8 64-bit, Windows 10 Pro, Windows 11 Pro, Windows 10 Pro Education, Windows 11 Pro Education.
The unit of measure for the Compatible products column.

The SSD, height column contains the height of the solid state drive in the notebook. The height is measured in millimeters and can be anywhere from 1.0 mm to 9.5 mm. The format of the height is a number.
The unit of measure for the SSD, height column.
The amount of memory a diskette drive has for a particular notebook computer. Ranges from 1.44 MB to 8.0 MB.
The unit of measure for the Diskette drive memory column.
The maximum altitude at which a notebook can operate. This is typically measured in meters and is usually around 3000 meters.
The unit of measure for the Maximum operating altitude column.

The maximum altitude at which the notebook can operate. This is typically measured in meters (m) and is a measure of how high the notebook can be stored or operated above sea level. The minimum value is 1.0 m, and the maximum value is 10668.0 m.
The unit of measure for the Maximum storage altitude column.

The number of pallets that can fit in a 20ft intermodal container. Typically, half a pallet is considered as one piece (or pc), so the number is usually an integer divided by 2, e.g. 20pc equals 10 pallets. The minimum and maximum values are 11 and 1700 respectively, but this is flexible.
The unit of measure for the Pallets per intermodal container (20ft) column.
A boolean value that describes whether the keyboard is built into the notebook or not. False if it is not built in, and true if it is.
The unit of measure for the Keyboard column.
The rate at which the display updates, measured in hertz (Hz). It is the number of times the display is refreshed every second.
The unit of measure for the Second display refresh rate column.
Features that can be used as alternatives to using a notebook for users with disabilities. This can include increase contrast, closed captions, and more.
The unit of measure for the Accessibility features column.

Refers to the presence of a composite video output on the notebook. This is an older video connection that is not as common as some other connections. The value in this column is an indication of the version of the composite video connection, with a minimum value of 1.0
The unit of measure for the Composite video in column.
The number of master cases of notebook computers that can fit in a single intermodal container (40ft).', 'min': '11.0 pc(s)', 'max': '5016.0 pc(s)

The CD-ROM DMA multi-mode (DMA mode 1) column contains the data transfer rate of the CD-ROM drive in megabytes per second. The value of this column is the maximum data transfer rate of the CD-ROM drive in megabytes per second. The CD-ROM DMA multi-mode (DMA mode 1) column is a measure of how fast the CD-ROM drive can transfer data from the CD-ROM to the computer's memory. The value of this column is the minimum data transfer rate of the CD-ROM drive in megabytes per second. The CD-ROM DMA multi-mode (DMA mode 1) column is a measure of how fast the CD-ROM drive can transfer data from the CD-ROM to the computer's memory. The value of this column is the minimum data transfer rate of the CD-ROM drive in megabytes per second. The CD-ROM DMA multi-mode (DMA mode 1) column is a measure of how fast the CD-ROM drive can transfer data from the CD-ROM to the computer's memory. The video modes display type refers to the type of display technology used in the notebook. The display type can be an LCD, OLED, or CRT.LCD displays are the most common type of display and use liquid crystals to create images. OLED displays use organic LEDs to create images and are known for their high contrast and deep blacks. CRT displays use cathode ray tubes to create images and are the oldest type of display technology.

Column Name Raw: Video modes maximum number of colours.1920
Column Name: Video modes maximum number of colours
Column Definition: The video modes maximum number of colours of a notebook is the maximum number of colours that the notebook can display.

Column Name Raw: Video modes maximum number of colours.1920.unit
Column Name: Video modes maximum number of colours_unit
Column Definition: The unit of measure for the Video modes maximum number of colours column.

The video modes maximum refresh rate (non-interlaced) is the maximum rate at which the notebook can refresh its video display. The refresh rate is measured in hertz (Hz), which is a measure of the number of frames per second that are displayed on the screen. The higher the refresh rate, the smoother the video display will appear. The video modes maximum refresh rate (non-interlaced) is the maximum refresh rate that the notebook can achieve when it is displaying a non-interlaced video signal. An interlace video signal is one in which the video frame is split into two separate fields, and the two fields are displayed in alternating order. The maximum refresh rate for an interlace video signal is half that of a non-interlaced video signal. Therefore, the video modes maximum refresh rate (non-interlaced) is twice the maximum refresh rate that the notebook can achieve when it is displaying an interlace video signal.
The unit of measure for the Video modes maximum refresh rate (non-interlaced) column.

A boolean that indicates whether the notebook has automatic resolution or not. If the notebook has automatic resolution, it means that the notebook can automatically adjust its display settings to suit the needs of the user. This includes features such as automatically adjusting the screen resolution to suit the size of the display, and automatically adjusting the color balance and brightness of the display to suit the ambient light conditions.
The unit of measure for the Auto resolution column.
A boolean value that indicates whether the notebook has SonicStage Mastering Studio or not. SonicStage Mastering Studio is a software to record, arrange and play sounds.
The unit of measure for the SonicStage Mastering Studio column.
A string indicating whether the notebook product can be configured to boot to a DVD. Values are either True or False.
The unit of measure for the Click to DVD column.
Whether the machine is Vaio branded or not. ('True' or 'False') Optional
The unit of measure for the Vaio Zone column.
Indicates which type of format the TV tuner on the notebook is. Options include: "Digital TV", "Analog TV", "Both" and null for no tuner.
The unit of measure for the TV tuner formats column.
A string that specifies the type of processor in the laptop. It needs to be one of the values from the following list: 1, 3, 5, 7, 9 or 11. The number indicates the generation of the processor.
The unit of measure for the QosmioEngine column.
The continuous audio playback time of the notebook, measured in hours. This value must be a float or integer followed by "h".
The unit of measure for the Continuous audio playback time column.
The unit of measure for the Bus type units column.
The unit of measure for the Bus type units column.

Whether the laptop has a Media Center remote control function or not. Options are 'Y' or 'N', where 'Y' denotes that it does and 'N' denotes that it does not. Third party, or unlisted, Media Center remote control functions should be denoted as '3'.
The unit of measure for the Media Center remote control function column.

The weight of the outer or master case of the product in grams. This is the weight of the entire container, not the weight of the product itself. This may equal the total weight of all the individual packages combined.
The unit of measure for the Master (outer) case net weight column.
The measured diagonal of the notebook display in centimeters or inches.
The unit of measure for the Notebook display diagonal (cm/inch) column.
The Ethernet adapter ARK ID refers to the unique identifier of the Ethernet adapter used in the notebook.
The unit of measure for the Ethernet adapter ARK ID column.
The number of pallets per intermodal container (40ft).
The unit of measure for the Pallets per intermodal container (40ft) column.
The number of pallets per intermodal container (40ft, high cube).
The unit of measure for the Pallets per intermodal container (40ft, HC) column.
The number of bytes that comprise each sector on the hard disk.
The unit of measure for the Bytes per sector column.
The number of sectors per track on the hard disk
The unit of measure for the Sectors per track column.
A string indicating whether the device has a smart friend subscription included. Values are either 'True' or 'False'.
The unit of measure for the HP SmartFriend column.
Boolean value that indicates whether the notebook has HP SmartFriend 2.0 preinstalled. If the notebook has HP SmartFriend 2.0 preinstalled, the value is True, otherwise the value is False.
The unit of measure for the HP SmartFriend 2.0 column.

The HP Expansion options column contains information about the expansion options of the HP notebook. The options are listed as a string of length 1, 2, or 3 characters. The options are as follows: '1' denotes an internal optical drive, '2' denotes an internal hard drive, and '3' denotes an external eSATA port.
The unit of measure for the HP Expansion options column.
The number of colours that the notebook product is available in. This can be a range of colours, for example, the product may be available in multiple shades of blue.
The unit of measure for the Number of colours column.
Amount of Polystyrene in grams that is contained in one package. Typically, this is an average value, and the actual Polystyrene content may vary per package.
The unit of measure for the Polystyrene (PS) content per package column.

Column Name Raw: Wheat straw molded pulp content per package.35320
Column Name: Wheat straw molded pulp content per package
Column Definition: The amount of wheat straw molded pulp that is contained in each package.

Column Name Raw: Wheat straw molded pulp content per package.35320.unit
Column Name: Wheat straw molded pulp content per package_unit
Column Definition: The unit of measure for the Wheat straw molded pulp content per package column.

A string that describes the resolution of a notebook. The resolution is the number of pixels in the horizontal and vertical dimensions of the notebook's display. The format of the resolution description is a string that contains two integers separated by a space. The first integer is the number of pixels in the horizontal dimension and the second integer is the number of pixels in the vertical dimension. For example, a resolution description of '1' means that the notebook has a display with a horizontal resolution of 1 pixel and a vertical resolution of 1 pixel.
The unit of measure for the Resolution description column.
The weight, measured in kilograms, of the outer packaging or carton for the notebook.
The unit of measure for the Gross weight of outer carton column.
Height of the outer packaging of the notebook, measured in centimeters. It ranges from 1.0 cm to 1.0 cm
The unit of measure for the Height (cm) outer carton column.
The length of the outer carton of the notebook, measured in centimeters. It has a minimum length of 1.0 cm.
The unit of measure for the Length (cm) outer carton column.
The weight, measured in kilograms, of the outer packaging or carton for the notebook.
The unit of measure for the Net weight of outer carton column.
The tare weight of the outer carton of the product, rounded to the nearest whole number. Note that this is different from the overall product weight, which can be found in the weight column.
The unit of measure for the Tare weight outer carton column.
Width of the outer packaging of the notebook, in centimeters. Note that this is the width of the packaging, not the width of the notebook itself.
The unit of measure for the Width (cm) outer carton column.
The weight of the packaging for the notebook. This column has a minimum value of 1.0 kg
The unit of measure for the Packaging net weight column.
The weight, measured in kilograms, of the packaging for the notebook. The packaging tare weight must be a positive numeric value.
The unit of measure for the Packaging tare weight column.
A string, containing the EAN/UPC/GTIN number of the packaging for the notebook.
The unit of measure for the EAN/UPC/GTIN (packaging) column.
A boolean which states whether or not the notebook comes with batteries included.
The unit of measure for the Batteries included column.
The size of the flash memory of the laptop. Minimum of 1.0 GB and a maximum of 2280.0 GB are available.
The unit of measure for the Flash memory column.
The type of shelf placement for the product.
The unit of measure for the Type of shelf-placement column.
The BitBlt column contains the BitBlt value of the notebook, which is an antenna that helps boost the signal strength of wireless network adapters. It is given in decibels (dBi).
The unit of measure for the BitBlt column.
Notebook dimension in imperial units, e.g. inches or feet
The unit of measure for the Dimension note (imperial) column.
The dimension note (metric) column contains the measurement of the notebook in centimeters. The measurement is a single integer value.
The unit of measure for the Dimension note (metric) column.
The standard memory note of the notebook. This is the amount of memory that is pre-installed on the notebook. It is measured in gigabytes (GB).
The unit of measure for the Standard memory note column.

Whether the notebook has stereo sound or not. Stereo sound is a two-channel audio reproduction system that creates an illusion of sound coming from various directions. It is sometimes referred to as "spatial sound".
The unit of measure for the Stereo sound column.

The browsing time is the time it takes to load a website or web page. It is typically measured in seconds or fractions of a second. The browsing time can vary depending on the website or web page being loaded, the number of users accessing the website or web page, the internet connection speed, and the hardware and software used to access the website or web page.
The unit of measure for the Browsing time column.
The accessories that are included with the notebook. This can include a charger, a case, a mouse, etc.
The unit of measure for the Accessories included column.

Column Name: Maximum number of colours (max video RAM)_unit

The total and available slots and bays for an expansion card to be installed in the notebook.
The unit of measure for the Total (available) slots & bays column.
Processors built into the laptop
The unit of measure for the Built-in processor column.
The unit of measure for the Camera type column.
The Mini-USB 2.0 ports quantity refers to the number of mini USB 2.0 ports that a laptop has. It ranges from 1.0 to 1.0
The unit of measure for the Mini-USB 2.0 ports quantity column.
A string that describes the amplifier of the notebook. This can either be 'Built-in' or 'External'.
The unit of measure for the Amplifier column.
Minimum hardware specifications required to run the operating system, including the central processing unit (CPU), random access memory (RAM), and storage drive.
The unit of measure for the Minimum system requirements column.

Supports direct 3D graphics acceleration. This indicates whether a graphic adapter supports DirectX 11 or higher which is necessary to run Maya and 3ds Max. (Y - Yes, N - No)

Date of the release of the notebook, in DD/MM/YYYY format
The unit of measure for the Release date (DD/MM/YYYY) column.
The video adapter resolution of the notebook. (e.g. 480p, 720p, 1080i)
The unit of measure for the Video adapter resolution column.
Indicates the energy efficiency of the notebook, according to the EU energy efficiency classification system.
The unit of measure for the Energy efficiency class column.
The maximum memory bandwidth of the notebook, in GB/s (Gigabytes per second).
